<emphasis id="70C3761D3660226FFEE2FA5E8527FA0A" box="[319,332,1412,1436]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="1572">n</emphasis>
= 12) 
<quantity id="854F07EA3660226FFE46FA5E867BFA0A" box="[411,528,1412,1436]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.132" pageId="30" pageNumber="1572" unit="mm" value="21.32">21.32 mm</quantity>
, 
<collectingRegion id="807364ED3660226FFDC1FA5E862BFA0A" box="[540,576,1412,1436]" country="Serbia" name="Sid" pageId="30" pageNumber="1572">SD</collectingRegion>
= 0.853).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4208AA0F3660226EFF4DFA1E8635FEB6" blockId="30.[144,1104,1476,1691]" lastBlockId="31.[212,1172,168,479]" lastPageId="31" lastPageNumber="1573" pageId="30" pageNumber="1572">
<emphasis id="70C3761D3660226FFF4DFA1E849AFA4A" box="[144,241,1476,1500]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="1572">Records.</emphasis>
This distinctive monotypic species occurs in riverine and dry forests from 
<collectingCountry id="3AA0EA9F3660226FFF4DFA3E854EFA6A" box="[144,293,1508,1532]" name="South Africa" pageId="30" pageNumber="1572">South Africa</collectingCountry>
northwards to eastern 
<collectingCountry id="3AA0EA9F3660226FFDE0FA3E86CDFA6A" box="[573,678,1508,1532]" name="Tanzania" pageId="30" pageNumber="1572">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
and northern 
<collectingCountry id="3AA0EA9F3660226FFC8AFA3E87CAFA6A" box="[855,929,1508,1532]" name="Kenya" pageId="30" pageNumber="1572">Kenya</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE3660226FFC68FA3E84AEF98A" author="Ackery PR &amp; Smith CR &amp; Vane-Wright RI" pageId="30" pageNumber="1572" refId="ref24360" refString="Ackery PR, Smith CR, Vane-Wright RI, editors. 1995. Carcasson' s African butterflies: an annotated catalogue of the Papilionoidea and Hesperioidea of the Afrotropical Region. East Melbourne (Australia): CSIRO." type="book" year="1995">Ackery et al. 1995</bibRefCitation>
, p.213). For 
<collectingCountry id="3AA0EA9F3660226FFE80F9DE85ADF98A" box="[349,454,1540,1564]" name="Tanzania" pageId="30" pageNumber="1572">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE3660226FFE12F9DE861DF98A" author="Kielland J" box="[463,630,1540,1564]" pageId="30" pageNumber="1572" refId="ref25501" refString="Kielland J. 1990. Butterflies of Tanzania. Melbourne: Hill House." type="book" year="1990">Kielland (1990</bibRefCitation>
, p.64) records 
<taxonomicName id="85B7D18C3660226FFCFFF9DE87FBF98A" baseAuthorityName="Spiller" baseAuthorityYear="1884" box="[802,912,1540,1564]" class="Insecta" family="Pieridae" genus="Dixeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="1572" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spilleri">
<emphasis id="70C3761D3660226FFCFFF9DE87FBF98A" box="[802,912,1540,1564]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="1572">D. spilleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a rather local bushland and forest roadside species found in coastal areas inland to Ifakara, Mikumi and the Usambaras, flying at altitudes up to 
<quantity id="854F07EA3660226FFD44F999869AF9CD" box="[665,753,1603,1627]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="30" pageNumber="1572" unit="m" value="1700.0">1700 m</quantity>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE3660226FFD22F99987DFF9CD" author="Cordeiro NJ" box="[767,948,1603,1627]" pageId="30" pageNumber="1572" pagination="194 - 198" refId="ref25176" refString="Cordeiro NJ. 1995. Interesting distribution records of butterflies from northern Tanzania. Metamorphosis. 6: 194 - 198." type="journal article" year="1995">Cordeiro (1995)</bibRefCitation>
noted an old specimen in BMNH from Moshi – but we failed to re-locate this material in the museum’ s main or Rothschild collections (perhaps the specimen was found among accession or supplementary material). However, given the details noted by Cordeiro, we think it unlikely he was mistaken. On this basis, and the evidence of 
<specimenCount id="54B161863661226EFBCFFF1280FFFF76" box="[1042,1172,200,224]" pageId="31" pageNumber="1573" type="male">three males</specimenCount>
from Taveta and a female from “Terta” in the BMNH, we include this butterfly as a member of the lower slopes fauna.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4208AA0F3661226EFF23FEF28557FE49" blockId="31.[212,1172,168,479]" pageId="31" pageNumber="1573">
Males of 
<taxonomicName id="85B7D18C3661226EFEB4FEF285BDFED6" baseAuthorityName="Spiller" baseAuthorityYear="1884" box="[361,470,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Pieridae" genus="Dixeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="1573" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spilleri">
<emphasis id="70C3761D3661226EFEB4FEF285BDFED6" box="[361,470,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="1573">D. spilleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are always a bright, clear yellow, while the females vary from white to cream or yellow (
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE3661226EFE23FE9286E2FEF6" author="Larsen TB" box="[510,649,328,352]" pageId="31" pageNumber="1573" refId="ref25550" refString="Larsen TB. 1996. The butterflies of Kenya and their natural history. 2 nd edn. Oxford (UK): Oxford University Press." type="book" year="1996">Larsen 1996</bibRefCitation>
, p.144, as “ 
<taxonomicName id="85B7D18C3661226EFCCFFE9287C5FEF6" baseAuthorityName="Spiller" baseAuthorityYear="1884" box="[786,942,328,352]" class="Insecta" family="Pieridae" genus="Dixeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="1573" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spilleri">
<emphasis id="70C3761D3661226EFCCFFE9287C5FEF6" box="[786,942,328,352]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="1573">spilleri spilleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”). Probably there is an underlying polymorphism in the females, which are generally yellow (male-like), piebald (forewing whitish, hindwing yellow or orangey-yellow), or whitish, with only the anal area of the hindwing with some orange scales. Worn specimens are difficult to assess.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
